Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00844727 Eh      5.30 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01386358 Eh      8.70 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04251403 Eh     26.68 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387303 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states

      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00774202 Eh      4.86 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387475 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04181994 Eh     26.24 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00775198 Eh      4.86 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387323 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04182840 Eh     26.25 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol

Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387323 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

                  0          1          2          3          4          5    
      0       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000
      1       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000
      2       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states

      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00774206 Eh      4.86 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387483 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00775172 Eh      4.86 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387334 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04182823 Eh     26.25 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol

Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387320 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol

Final entropy term                ...      0.04182708 Eh     26.25 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00774921 Eh      4.86 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387329 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04182568 Eh     26.25 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES

M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00775052 Eh      4.86 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01387318 Eh      8.71 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01916589 Eh     12.03 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04182688 Eh     26.25 kcal/mol
